<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910123-0106</DOCNO><DOCID>910123-0106.</DOCID><HL>   South Africa's Trade Surplus</HL><DATE>01/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AFRIC</CO><IN>INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (IEI)INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)</IN><LP>   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- The nation's trade surpluswidened 15% to 1.88 billion rand ($733.6 million) in Decemberfrom 1.64 billion rand a year earlier and expanded 25% from1.5 billion rand in November, the government said.   The figures aren't seasonally adjusted, but export andimport data are adjusted to bring them in line withrequirements for compiling the nation's balance of payments.Exports for December totaled 4.96 billion rand, up 8% from ayear earlier, and imports amounted to 3.08 billion rand, up4%.</LP><TEXT>   For 1990, exports rose 3% to 60.57 billion rand, comparedwith 1989, and imports declined 1% to 44.21 billion rand.   The trade figures include South Africa's exports of goldbullion, the country's principal source of foreign exchangeearnings. Imports include the country's purchases of oil andother petroleum products, despite the longstanding embargo bythe Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.</TEXT></DOC>